outh and Central America constitute one of the greatest concentrations of aquatic diversity on Earth, consisting of about 10 percent of all living vertebrate species. Historical Biogeography of Neotropical Freshwater Fishes explores the evolutionary origins of this unique ecosystem. The chapters address central themes in the study of tropical biodiversity: why is the Amazon basin home to so many distinct evolutionary lineages? What roles do ecological specialization, speciation, and extinction play in the formation of regional assemblages? How do dispersal barriers contribute to isolation and diversification? Focusing on whole faunas rather than individual taxonomic groups, this volume shows that the area’s high regional diversity is not the result of recent diversification in lowland tropical rainforests. Rather, it is the product of species accumulating over tens of millions of years and across a continental arena.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBiodiversityzLatin America. 0aFreshwater fisheszLatin AmericaxGeographical distributionxHistory. 0aFreshwater fisheszLatin AmericaxGeographical distribution. 0aFreshwater fisheszLatin AmericaxPhylogeny. 0aHistorical geologyzLatin America. 0aPaleoecologyzLatin America. 0aZoogeographyzLatin America. 70(DE-601)1061469980(DE-588)4058509-8aSüßwasserfische2gnd 70(DE-601)1640566020(DE-588)4350465-6aPaläobiogeografie2gnd 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Ichthyology & Herpetology.2bisacsh  aamazon basin.  aanimal populations.  abiodiversity.  abiology.  acentral america.  aconservation.  adiversification.  aearth sciences.  aecological specialization.  aecology.  aenvironment.  aenvironmentalism.  aextinct animals.  afauna.  afish.  ageography.  ahistorical biogeography.  aichthyology.  alife sciences.  a